1976\n| arena       = [[Salem Civic Center]] (1967\u20131976)<br>[[Berglund Center|Roanoke Civic Center]] (1971\u20131976)\n| colors      = Blue, red, white<br>{{color box|blue}} {{color box|red}} {{color box|white}}\n| affiliates  = [[National Hockey League|NHL]] (1971\u20131972)<br>[[World Hockey Association|WHA]] (1972\u20131976)\n<!---Franchise history--->\n| name1       = Salem Rebels\n| dates1      = 1967\u20131970\n| name2       = Roanoke Valley Rebels\n| dates2      = 1970\u20131976\n|championships= [[1973\u201374 Southern Hockey League season|1973\u201374]] (SHL)\n}}\n\nThe '''Roanoke Valley Rebels''' were a minor league professional ice hockey team based in the [[Roanoke Valley]] in Virginia. The team first played in the [[Eastern Hockey League]] and then joined the [[Southern Hockey League (1973\u201377)|Southern Hockey League]]. The team was originally known as the '''Salem Rebels''' from 1967 to 1970, playing at the [[Salem Civic Center]] in [[Salem, Virginia]].<ref name=\"salem\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/stte/salem-rebels-7832.html|title=Salem Rebels hockey team statistics and history|website=hockeydb.com|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref> In 1971, the Rebels began splitting home games between Salem at the newer and larger [[Berglund Center|Roanoke Civic Center]] in [[Roanoke, Virginia|Roanoke]].<ref name=\"ehl-stats\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/stte/roanoke-valley-rebels-7726.html|title=Roanoke Valley Rebels hockey team [EHL] statistics and history|website=hockeydb.com|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref><ref name=\"Turner\">{{cite web|url=http://theroanokestar.com/2017/10/02/pro-ice-hockey-celebrates-50th-anniversary-in-roanoke-valley/|title=Pro Ice Hockey Celebrates 50th Anniversary In Roanoke Valley|last=Turner|first=Bill|date=2017-10-02|website=The Roanoke Star|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref> \n\nThe team name was recalled [[Johnny Reb]], a [[national personification]] of the [[Southern United States]]. The team logo resembled the ''[[Flags of the Confederate States of America|Battle Flag]]'' of the [[Confederate States of America]]. The Rebels were founding members of the Southern Hockey League in 1973 after the Eastern Hockey League ceased operations, and won the James Crockett Cup in 1974.<ref name=\"hockeydb-shl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/leagues/229.html|title=Southern Hockey League [1973-1977] history and statistics|website=hockeydb.com|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref> After nine seasons of play, the team ceased operations in 1976.<ref name=\"shl=stats\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/stte/roanoke-valley-rebels-7727.html|title=Roanoke Valley Rebels hockey team [SHL] statistics and history|website=hockeydb.com|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe first Salem Rebels game was played October 24, 1967, and Salem won 3\u20131 over the [[Jacksonville Rockets]].<ref name=\"Turner\" /> Most of the players lived in a mobile home park across, near the [[Lakeside Amusement Park (Virginia)|Lakeside Amusement Park]].<ref name=\"Turner\" /> [[Dave Lucas]] was coach the team's first coach, but struggled for the first two seasons and missed the playoffs both years.<ref name=\"salem\" /> Colin Kilburn was brought in to coach in 1969, and improved the team to second place in the southern division, but lost in the first round of the playoffs.<ref name=\"salem\" /> Kilburn coached the next two seasons to third place finishes, and first round playoff losses.<ref name=\"ehl-stats\" /> The Rebels affiliated with the [[Philadelphia Blazers]] in 1972 and the parent club assigned [[Gregg Pilling]] to coach. The Rebels finished first place in the southern division, won two playoff series, and finished runners-up in the 1973 EHL finals.<ref name=\"ehl-stats\" /> \n\nIn 1973, the Rebels became a charter team in the Southern Hockey League due to travel costs to the multiple northern teams in the EHL for the 1973\u201374 season. Pilling stayed on as coach and the team roster featured eleven [[French Canadians]], including the league's most valuable player, Claude Piche.<ref name=\"Turner\" /> The Rebels finished first place in the regular season, and won the James Crocket Cup in the playoffs.<ref name=\"shl=stats\" /> Pilling was named the SHL Coach of the Year for 1973\u201374.<ref name=\"Turner\" /> [[Bill Needham]] coached the 1974\u201375 season, and the team dropped to fourth place and a first round playoff loss.\n\nTeam operator and league commissioner, Gene Hawthorne, filed for bankruptcy protection for the team July 14, 1975,<ref>{{cite news|title=Roanoke Rebels are Bankrupt|newspaper=Petersburg Progress|location=Petersburg, Virginia|date=July 15, 1975|page=8|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jul-15-1975-578695/}}{{free access}}</ref> and the Rebels were obtained by local oil distributor, [[Henry Brabham]]. Player-coach [[Jack Chipchase]] led the Rebels in the 1975\u201376 season, finishing fourth place, and a first round playoff loss. The Rebels ceased operations after the season.<ref name=\"shl=stats\" /> Salem eventually got another team in the [[Salem Raiders]] of the restarted [[Eastern Hockey League (1978\u20131981)|Eastern Hockey League]] in 1980 and the [[Roanoke Valley Rebels (ECHL)|Rebels branding]] was revived for an [[East Coast Hockey League]] team from 1990 to 1992.\n\n===Major league affiliations===\nThe Rebels were affiliated with the [[National Hockey League]] in the 1971\u201372 season, and with the [[World Hockey Association]] from 1972 to 1976.<ref name=\"ehl-affiliates\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/display_affiliations_child.php?tmi=7726|title=Roanoke Valley Rebels Parent Team affiliate history|website=hockeydb.com|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref><ref name=\"shl-affiliates\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/display_affiliations_child.php?tmi=7727|title=Roanoke Valley Rebels Parent Team affiliate history|website=hockeydb.com|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Years!!Affiliations\n|- \t\n|1971\u201372|| [[Philadelphia Flyers]]\n|- \t\n|1972\u201373|| [[Philadelphia Blazers]]\n|- \t\n|1973\u201374|| [[Vancouver Blazers]]\n|- \t\n|1974\u201375|| [[Houston Aeros (WHA)|Houston Aeros]], [[Winnipeg Jets (1972\u201396)|Winnipeg Jets]]\n|- \t\n|1975\u201376|| [[Calgary Cowboys]], [[San Diego Mariners]], Winnipeg Jets \n|}\n\n==Notable players==\nNotable players for the Salem Rebels (EHL 1967\u20131970),<ref name=\"salem-ehl-players\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/display_players.php?tmi=7832|title=Salem Rebels all-time player list|website=hockeydb.com|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref> the Roanoke Valley Rebels (EHL 1970\u20131973),<ref name=\"ehl-players\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/display_players.php?tmi=7726|title=Roanoke Valley Rebels [EHL] all-time player list|website=hockeydb.com|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref> and the Roanoke Valley Rebels (SHL 1973\u20131977),<ref name=\"shl-players\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/display_players.php?tmi=7727|title=Roanoke Valley Rebels [SHL] all-time player list|website=hockeydb.com|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref> who also played in either the National Hockey League or the World Hockey Association.\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=10em}}\n*[[Randy Andreachuk]]\n*[[Yves Archambault]]\n*[[Ron Ashton]]\n*[[Jamie Bateman]]\n*[[Serge Beaudoin]]\n*[[John Bennett (ice hockey)|John Bennett]]\n*[[Michel Boudreau]]\n*[[Brian Bradley (ice hockey, born 1944)|Brian Bradley]]\n*[[Brian Bye]]\n*[[Rychard Campeau]]\n*[[Mike Chernoff (ice hockey)|Mike Chernoff]]\n*[[Jack Chipchase]]\n*[[Howie Colborne]]\n*[[Pete Donnelly (ice hockey)|Pete Donnelly]]\n*[[Guy Dufour (ice hockey)|Guy Dufour]]\n*[[George Gardner (ice hockey)|George Gardner]]\n*[[Jean-Claude Garneau]]\n*[[Sam Gellard]]\n*[[Merv Haney]]\n*[[Derek Harker]]\n*[[Pierre Henry (ice hockey)|Pierre Henry]]\n*[[Ted Hodgson]]\n*[[Ralph Hopiavuori]]\n*[[Ed Humphreys]]\n*[[Dave Hutchison (ice hockey)|Dave Hutchison]]\n*[[Jim Jones (ice hockey)|Jim Jones]]\n*[[Jimmy Jones (ice hockey)|Jimmy Jones]]\n*[[Joe Junkin]]\n*[[Doug Kerslake]]\n*[[Roger Lafreniere]]\n*[[Camille LaPierre]]\n*[[Dave Lucas]]\n*[[Peter McNamee]]\n*[[Denis Meloche]]\n*[[John Migneault]]\n*[[Wayne Mosdell]]\n*[[Murray Myers]]\n*[[Billy Orr (ice hockey)|Billy Orr]]\n*[[Pierre Paiement]]\n*[[Michel Plante]]\n*[[Jan Popiel]]\n*[[Rich Pumple]]\n*[[Michel Rouleau]]\n*[[Claude St. Sauveur]]\n*[[Dave Schultz (ice hockey)|Dave Schultz]]\n*[[Gord Smith (ice hockey)|Gord Smith]]\n*[[Daniel Sullivan (ice hockey, born 1947)|Danny Sullivan]]\n*[[Jean T\u00e9treault]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Results==\nAs recorded in the Internet Hockey Database:<ref name=\"salem\" /><ref name=\"ehl-stats\" /><ref name=\"shl=stats\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Season!!Lge!!GP!!W!!L!!T!!Pts!!Pct!!GF!!GA!!PIM!!Standing!!Playoffs\n|-\n|1967\u201368||EHL||72||11||53|| 8|| 30||0.208||211||432|| 880||6th, Southern||Did not qualify\n|-\n|1968\u201369||EHL||72||24||45|| 3|| 51||0.354||240||321|| 786||5th, Southern||Did not qualify\n|-\n|1969\u201370||EHL||74||37||27||10|| 84||0.568||279||266||1272||2nd, Southern||Lost in round 1\n|-\n|1970\u201371||EHL||74||31||34|| 9|| 71||0.480||257||303||1071||3rd, Southern||Lost in round 1\n|-\n|1971\u201372||EHL||73||30||33||10|| 70||0.479||241||266|| 968||3rd, Southern||Lost in round 1\n|-\n|1972\u201373||EHL||76||40||25||11|| 91||0.599||345||276||1629||'''1st, Southern'''||Lost in finals\n|-\n|[[1973\u201374 Southern Hockey League season|1973\u201374]]||SHL||72||53||19|| 0||106||0.736||366||244||1458||'''1st, SHL'''||'''Won championship'''\n|-\n|[[1974\u201375 Southern Hockey League season|1974\u201375]]||SHL||72||29||41|| 2|| 60||0.417||296||304||1037||4th, SHL||Lost in round 1\n|-\n|[[1975\u201376 Southern Hockey League season|1975\u201376]]||SHL||72||29||28||15|| 73||0.507||239||238||1224||4th, SHL||Lost in round 1\n|-\n!TOTALS!!EHL!!441!!173!!217!!51!!397!!0.450!!1