{"title_page": "Arthur Spry", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n'''Arthur Spry''' (4 February 1612 \u2013 17 September 1685) was an English politician who sat in the [[House of Commons of England|House of Commons]] from 1660 to 1679.\n[[File:Place House, St Anthony - geograph.org.uk - 29332.jpg|thumb|Place House]]\nSpry was the son of Thomas Spry and his wife Catherine Ashford, daughter of Arthur Ashford. He was the first member of the family to settle at Place, a property granted to the Spry family by Henry VIII, in the parish of [[St Anthony in Roseland]].<ref name=Burke>[https://books.google.com/books?id=KikAAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA691&lpg=PA691&dq=%22Arthur+Spry%22+Mawes&source=bl&ots=OVizVEu1y2&sig=3fEYrMSqR0bn65aWcr_GrO9zgvY&hl=en&ei=1UEOTrGLN8-ZhQehxIHHDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&sqi=2&ved=0CDIQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22Arthur%20Spry%22%20Mawes&f=false John Burke ''A genealogical and heraldic history of the commoners of Great Britain'']</ref>\nIn 1660, Spry was elected [[Member of Parliament]] for [[St Mawes (UK Parliament constituency)|St Mawes]] in the [[Convention Parliament (1660)|Convention Parliament]] being seated after a double return in May 1660.<ref name=LR>{{Rayment-hc|s|1|date=March 2012}}</ref>  In 1661 he was re-elected MP for St Mawes in another double return to the [[Cavalier Parliament]] and was seated in May. He sat until 1679.<ref name=LR/>\n\nSpry died at the age of  73 and was buried at [[St Anthony's Church, St Anthony in Roseland|St Anthony's]] where a monument was erected featuring a bust between two weeping females.<ref name=Burke/>\n\nSpry married firstly Mary Gayer daughter of Richard Gayer. She died on 4 May 1656 and was buried at Anthony Church. He married secondly Luce Hele, daughter of George Hele. He had a son George and was grandfather of the admiral [[Richard Spry]].<ref name=Burke/>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spry, Arthur}}\n[[Category:1612 births]]\n[[Category:1685 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the pre-1707 English Parliament for constituencies in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cornwall]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1660]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1661\u20131679]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n'''Arthur Spry''' (4 February 1612 \u2013 17 September 1685) was an English politician who sat in the [[House of Commons of England|House of Commons]] from 1660 to 1679.\n[[File:Place House, St Anthony - geograph.org.uk - 29332.jpg|thumb|Place House]]\nSpry was the son of Thomas Spry and his wife Catherine Ashford, daughter of Arthur Ashford. He was the first member of the family to settle at Place, a property granted to the Spry family by Henry VIII, in the parish of [[St Anthony in Roseland]].<ref name=Burke>[https://books.google.com/books?id=KikAAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA691&lpg=PA691&dq=%22Arthur+Spry%22+Mawes&source=bl&ots=OVizVEu1y2&sig=3fEYrMSqR0bn65aWcr_GrO9zgvY&hl=en&ei=1UEOTrGLN8-ZhQehxIHHDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&sqi=2&ved=0CDIQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22Arthur%20Spry%22%20Mawes&f=false John Burke ''A genealogical and heraldic history of the commoners of Great Britain'']</ref>\nIn 1660, Spry was elected [[Member of Parliament]] for [[St Mawes (UK Parliament constituency)|St Mawes]] in the [[Convention Parliament (1660)|Convention Parliament]] being seated after a double return in May 1660.<ref name=LR>{{Rayment-hc|s|1|date=March 2012}}</ref>  In 1661 he was re-elected MP for St Mawes in another double return to the [[Cavalier Parliament]] and was seated in May. He sat until 1679.<ref name=LR/>\n\nSpry died at the age of  73 and was buried at [[St Anthony's Church, St Anthony in Roseland|St Anthony's]] where a monument was erected featuring a bust between two weeping females.<ref name=Burke/>\n\nSpry married firstly Mary Gayer daughter of Richard Gayer. She died on 4 May 1656 and was buried at Anthony Church. He married secondly Luce Hele, daughter of George Hele. He had a son George and was grandfather of the admiral [[Richard Spry]].<ref name=Burke/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spry, Arthur}}\n[[Category:1612 births]]\n[[Category:1685 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the pre-1707 English Parliament for constituencies in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cornwall]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1660]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1661\u20131679]]\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_Spry"}
{"title_page": "Alexander Griboyedov", "text_new": "{{short description|Russian diplomat, playwright, poet, and composer}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| nickname = \n| image = Griboyedov.jpg\n| caption = Portrait by [[Ivan Kramskoi]]\n| ambassador_from = Russian\n| country = Iran\n| monarch1 = [[Nicholas I of Russia]]\n| primeminister1 = \n| term_start1 = 1828<ref>{{cite book|last1=Borrero|first1=Mauricio|title=Russia: A Reference Guide from the Renaissance to the Present|date=2009|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-0816074754|page=169|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dhm0cGdrTOIC&pg=PA169&dq=griboyedov+appointed+ambassador+1828&hl=nl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQz5P_9sHKAhXJwBQKHUJhC2gQ6AEIMzAC#v=onepage&q=griboyedov%20appointed%20ambassador%201828&f=false}}</ref>\n| term_end1 = 1829\n| predecessor1 = \n| successor1 = \n| office2 = \n| primeminister2 = \n| term_start2 = \n| term_end2 = \n| constituency2 = \n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 = \n| office3 = \n| monarch3 = \n| primeminister3 = \n| term_start3 = \n| term_end3 = \n| predecessor3 = \n| successor3 = \n| birth_name = Alexander Sergeyevich Griboyedov\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1795|01|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Moscow]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1829|02|11|1795|01|15|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Tehran]], [[Qajar Iran]]\n| nationality = [[Imperial Russia|Russian]]\n| residence = \n| restingplace = [[Tiflis]], Russian Empire <small>(present-day [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]])\n| alma_mater = [[Imperial Moscow University|Imperial Moscow University (1808)]]\n| party = \n| otherparty = \n| spouse = [[Nino Chavchavadze]]\n| children = \n| occupation = Diplomat, Playwright, Poet, and Composer\n| profession = \n| cabinet = \n| religion = \n| signature = Griboyedov_Signature.jpg\n| awards = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| blank1 = \n| data1 = \n}}\n'''Alexander Sergeyevich Griboyedov''' ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0413\u0440\u0438\u0431\u043e\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432}}, ''Aleksandr Sergeevich Griboedov'' or ''Sergeevich Griboyedov''; 15 January 1795{{snd}}11 February 1829), formerly [[romanization of Russian|romanized]] as '''Alexander Sergueevich Griboyedoff''',<ref>\"Griboyedoff, Alexander Sergueevich\" in the ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]'', {{nowrap|9th ed.}}, {{nowrap|Vol. XI}} 1880.</ref> was a Russian [[diplomat]], [[playwright]], [[poet]], and [[composer]]. He is recognized as ''[[homo unius libri]]'', a writer of one book, whose fame rests on the verse comedy ''[[Woe from Wit]]'' or ''The Woes of Wit''. He was Russia's ambassador to [[Qajar Iran|Qajar Persia]], where he and all the embassy staff were massacred by an [[angry mob]] as a result of the rampant anti-Russian sentiment that existed through Russia's imposing of the [[Treaty of Gulistan]] (1813) and [[Treaty of Turkmenchay]] (1828), which had forcefully ratified for Persia's ceding of its northern territories comprising [[Transcaucasia]] and parts of the [[North Caucasus]]. Griboyedov had played a pivotal role in the ratification of the latter treaty.\n\n==Early life==\nGriboyedov was born in [[Moscow]], the exact year unknown, with biographers debating whether it was in 1790 or 1795. Griboyedov received a Masters in [[philology]] from [[Moscow State University|Moscow University]], and subsequently enrolled in the doctorate program. In 1812, he quit the program and enrolled in the military.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Woe from Wit|last=Griboyedov|first=Alexander|publisher=Russian Life Books|year=2017|isbn=978-1-880100-52-3|location=Montpelier, VT|pages=6\u20137}}</ref> He obtained a commission in a [[hussar]] [[regiment]], which he resigned in 1816. The next year, he entered the [[civil service]]. In 1818 he was appointed secretary of the Russian [[legation]] in [[Persia]], and transferred to [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{EB1911|inline=y|wstitle=Griboyedov, Alexander Sergueevich|volume=12|page=593}}</ref>\n\nHis [[Poetry|verse]] comedy ''The Young Spouses'' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u0443\u043f\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0438}}, ''Molodye Suprugi''), which he staged in [[St. Petersburg]] in 1816, was followed by other similar works. Neither these nor his [[essay]]s and poetry would have been long remembered but for the success of his verse comedy ''[[Woe from Wit]]'' ({{lang-ru|\u0413\u043e\u0440\u0435 \u043e\u0442 \u0443\u043c\u0430}}, ''Gore ot Uma''), a [[satire]] on Russian [[aristocracy (class)|aristocratic]] society.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/>\n\nAs a high official in the play puts it, this work is \"a [[pasquinade]] on Moscow\". The play depicts certain social and official stereotypes in the characters of Famusov, who hates reform; his secretary, Molchalin, who fawns over officials; and the aristocratic young liberal and [[Anglomania]]c, Repetilov. By contrast the hero of the piece, Chatsky, an ironic satirist just returned from western Europe, exposes and ridicules the weaknesses of the rest. His words echo the outcry of the young generation in the lead-up to the [[Decembrist|armed insurrection of 1825]].<ref name=\"EB1911\"/>\n\nIn [[Russia]] for the summer of 1823, Griboyedov completed the play and took it to St. Petersburg. It was rejected by the [[censorship|censors]]. Many copies were made and privately circulated, but Griboyedov never saw it published.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/> After his death the manuscript was jointly owned by his wife [[Nino Chavchavadze|Nina Alexandrovna Griboyedova]] and his sister [[Maria Sergeyevna Durnovo (Griboyedova)]].<ref>{{cite magazine|script-title=ru:\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u041e\u0431 \u0410. \u0421. \u0413\u0440\u0438\u0431\u043e\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0435 |trans-title=A note about A. S. Griboyedov |edition=reprint |magazine=Russian Messenger |year=1892 |issue=8 |access-date=29 January 2017 |language=ru |pages=335\u2013347|url=http://feb-web.ru/feb/griboed/critics/vos80/vos_comm.htm }}</ref> The first edition was not published until 1833, four years after his death. Only once did he see it on the stage, when it was performed by the officers of the garrison at [[Yerevan]]. Soured by disappointment, he returned to Georgia. During the [[Russo-Persian War, 1826-1828|Russo-Persian War of 1826\u20131828]], he put his [[Linguistics|linguistic]] expertise at the service of general [[Ivan Paskevich]], a relative; after which he was sent to St. Petersburg where he worked on the [[Treaty of Turkmenchay]] negotiations. There, thinking to devote himself to [[literature]], he started work on a romantic drama, ''A Georgian Night'' ({{lang-ru|\u0413\u0440\u0443\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043d\u043e\u0447\u044c}}, ''Gruzinskaya noch''), based on Georgian legends.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Monument of Alexander Griboyedov in Dilijan Armenia.jpg|thumb|left|Monument erected in Soviet times in [[Dilijan]], [[Armenia]] commemorating the location where [[Alexander Pushkin]] (on his way to meet his brother) stopped the carriage with Alexander Griboyedov's body being transported to [[Tiflis]]. An inscription in Russian and Armenian says: \"Here A. S. Pushkin saw the body of A. S. Griboyedov\".]]\n\nSeveral months after his wedding to [[Nino Chavchavadze|Nino]], 16-year-old daughter of his friend [[Alexander Chavchavadze|Prince Chavchavadze]], Griboyedov was suddenly sent to Persia as [[Minister Plenipotentiary]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} In the aftermath of the [[Russo-Persian War (1826-1828)|war]] and the humiliating [[Treaty of Turkmenchay]], there was strong [[anti-Russian sentiment]] in Persia. Soon after Griboyedov's arrival in [[Tehran]], a mob stormed the [[Embassy of Russia in Tehran|Russian embassy]].\n\nThe incident began when an [[Armenians|Armenian]] [[Eunuch (court official)|eunuch]] escaped from the [[harem]] of the Persian [[Fath Ali Shah|shah]], and at the same time two enslaved Armenian women escaped from the harem of the Shah's son-in-law. All three sought refuge at the Russian legation. As agreed in the [[Treaty of Turkmenchay]], Georgians and Armenians living in Persia at that time were permitted to return to Georgia and [[Eastern Armenia]].<ref name=\"Hopkirk p. 122\">[[Peter Hopkirk|Hopkirk, Peter]]. ''[[The Great Game: The Struggle for Empire in Central Asia]]''. New York: Kodansha Globe, 1997 p. 122 {{ISBN|1-56836-022-3}}</ref> However, the Shah demanded that Griboyedov return the three escapees. Griboyedov refused. His decision caused an uproar throughout the city and several thousand Persians encircled the Russian compound demanding their release.\n\nWhen Griboyedov decided to return the escaped eunuch and two Armenian women, it was too late. Soon after, urged on by the mullahs, the mob stormed the building. A high-ranking Muslim scholar with the title of Mojtahed, Mirza Masih Astarabadi known as Mirza Masih Mojtahed, issued a fatwa saying that freeing Muslim women from the claws of unbelievers is allowed.<ref name=Hopkirk>{{cite book |title=The Great Game |last=Hopkirk |first=Peter |year=2006 |publisher=John Murray |location=London |isbn=978-0-7195-6447-5 |page=113}}</ref>\n\nGriboyedov and other members of his mission had prepared for a siege and sealed all the windows and doors. Armed and in full uniform, they were resolved to defend to the last drop of blood. Although small in number, the [[Cossack]] detachment assigned to protect the legation held off the mob for over an hour until finally being driven back to Griboyedov's office. There, Griboyedov and the Cossacks resisted until the mob broke through the roof of the building, and then through the ceiling, to slaughter them. The escaped eunuch and Griboyedov, who fought with his sword, were among the first to be shot to death; the fate of the two Armenian women remains unknown.<ref name=\"Hopkirk p. 122\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Baron K. K. Bode|title=Griboyedov's Death|url= http://feb-web.ru/feb/griboed/critics/vos29/bode_29.htm|website=www.feb-web.ru}}</ref> Second secretary of the mission Karl Adelung and, in particular, a young doctor whose name is not known, fought hard, but soon the scene was one of butchered, decapitated corpses.\n\nGriboyedov's body, thrown from a window, was decapitated by a kebab vendor who displayed the head on his stall.<ref name=Hopkirk/> The mob dragged the uniformed corpse through the city's streets and bazaars, to cries of celebration. It was eventually abandoned on a garbage heap after three days of ill-treatment by the mob, such that in the end it could be identified only by a duelling injury to a finger. The following June, Griboyedov's friend [[Alexander Pushkin]], travelling through the southern Caucasus, encountered some men from Tehran leading an oxcart. The men told Pushkin they were conveying the ambassador's remains to Tiflis (now [[Tbilisi]]).\nGriboyedov was buried there, in the monastery of St. David ([[Mtatsminda Pantheon]]).<ref name=Hopkirk/>\n\nWhen Nino, Griboyedov's widow, received news of his death she gave premature birth to a child who died a few hours later. Nino lived another thirty years, rejecting all suitors and winning universal admiration for her fidelity to her husband's memory.\n\nIn a move to compensate Russia for the attack and the death of its ambassador, the Shah sent his grandson [[Khosrow Mirza]] to St. Petersburg to avoid another war with [[Tsar Nicholas I]].<ref name=Hopkirk/><ref>George Bournoutian (2014) ''From Tabriz to St. Petersburg: Iran's Mission of Apology to Russia in 1829''</ref> and also gifted to him the [[Shah Diamond]].<ref name=\"Tharoor\">{{Cite news|first=Ishaan |last=Tharoor |title=A Russian ambassador was murdered: The apology came in the shape of a huge diamond |date=22 December 2016 |newspaper=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/12/22/a-russian-ambassador-was-murdered-the-apology-came-in-the-shape-of-a-huge-diamond/ |access-date=29 January 2017 }}</ref>\n\nRussian sources claim that<ref name=\"BournoutianIRA\" /> British agents, who feared Russian influence in Tehran, and Persian reactionaries, who were not satisfied with the Turkmenchay treaty, were responsible for inciting the mob.<ref name=\"BournoutianIRA\" /> The death of Griboyedov, who was a liberal and who advocated regional autonomy for the Christians in Transcaucasia, was probably not a great loss for Tsar Nicholas or General Paskevich, both of whom wished to Russianize the minorities in the Caucasus.{{fact|date=January 2020}} The [[Russo-Turkish War (1828\u201329)]] might have been another reason for the Russian inaction.<ref name=BournoutianIRA>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Bournoutian |first=George| title=Griboyedov, Alexander Sergeevich | encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica | accessdate=2016-02-02|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/griboedov-alexander-sergeevich}}</ref> His wife had written on his tombstone in Tiflis:  \u201cYour mind and works are immortal in Russian memory, but why has my love outlived you?\u201d.<ref name=\"Tharoor\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Moscow Aleksander Griboyedov monument.JPG|thumb|Monument in Moscow]]\n[[File:Griboyedov monument 9122262 22.JPG|thumb|Griboyedov's statue in [[Yerevan]], Armenia]]\nAuthor Angela Brintlinger has said that \"not only did Griboyedov's contemporaries conceive of his life as the life of a literary hero\u2014ultimately writing a number of narratives featuring him as an essential character\u2014but indeed Griboyedov saw himself as a hero and his life as a narrative. Although there is not a literary artifact to prove this, by examining Griboyedov's letters and dispatches, one is able to build a historical narrative that fits the literary and behavioural paradigms of his time and that reads like a real adventure novel set in the wild, wild East.\"\n\nOne of the main settings for [[Mikhail Bulgakov]]'s satirical novel ''[[The Master and Margarita]]'' is named after Griboyedov, as is the [[Griboedov Canal|Griboyedov Canal]] in [[Central Saint Petersburg]]. One of the central streets of [[Tbilisi]], the capital of [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], is named after Griboyedov. This street is crossed by Alexander Chavchavadze street, named after Griboyedov's father-in-law, famous Georgian poet, [[Alexander Chavchavadze]].\n\nOn 17 April 1944 Pravda ran a lengthy feature on the commemoration of Griboyedov's 150th birthday when high-ranking officials, military leaders, diplomats, writers, and artists had attended a celebration in the [[Bolshoi Theatre]]. Novelist and Stalin deputy [[Leonid Leonov]] eulogized Griboyedov, mentioning especially his love of his fatherland.\n\nThe reception to the Shah's grandson Khosrow Mirza in the [[Winter Palace]], and Tsar Nicholas receiving from him the Shah Diamond, are featured in the 2002 Russian film ''[[Russian Ark]]''.\n\n==Commemoration==\n\n===Monuments===\n* In [[Saint Petersburg]], the monument of A.S. Griboyedov (sculptor V.V. Lishev, 1959) is located on Zagorodny Prospekt on Pionerskaya Square (in front of the [[Bryantsev Youth Theatre]])\n* In the center of [[Yerevan]] there is a monument of A.S. Griboyedov (author - Hovhannes Bejanyan, 1974).\n* In [[Alushta]], a monument of A.S. Griboyedov was erected in 2002, on the 100th anniversary of the city.\n* In [[Moscow]], the monument of A.S. Griboyedov is located on Chistoprudny Boulevard.\n* In [[Veliky Novgorod]], A.S. Griboyedov was immortalized in the monument \u201c[[Millennium of Russia]]\u201d, in the group of sculptures \u201cWriters and Artists\u201d.\n* In [[Volgograd]], at the expense of the Armenian community of the city, a bust of A.S. Griboyedov was installed on Sovetskaya Street, in front of Polyclinic \u21163.\n* In [[Tbilisi]], a monument of A.S. Griboyedov is located on the Kura embankment (sculptor M. Merabishvili, architect G. Melkadze, 1961).\n* In [[Tehran]], the Russian [[embassy]] has a monument of A.S. Griboyedov (sculptor V. A. Beklemishev, 1912).\n* A bust of A. S. Griboyedov is installed on the facade of the [[Odessa Opera and Ballet Theater]].\n\n=== Streets ===\nThere are streets n.a. Griboyedov in many cities of Russia and neighboring countries.\n\n{{Hidden\n|List of places\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n| content = '''[[Russia]]'''\n\n* [[Almetyevsk]],\n* [[Petrozavodsk]],\n* [[Perm]],\n* [[Chelyabinsk]],\n* [[Krasnoyarsk]],\n* [[Kaliningrad]],\n* [[Surgut]],\n* [[Simferopol]],\n* [[Sevastopol]],\n* [[Bryansk]],\n* [[Ekaterinburg]],\n* [[Novokuznetsk]],\n* [[Novorossiysk]],\n* [[Novosibirsk]],\n* [[Ryazan]],\n* [[Dzerzhinsk, Russia|Dzerzhinsk]] (Nizhny Novgorod Oblast),\n* [[Irkutsk]],\n* [[Makhachkala]],\n* [[Gelendzhik]],\n* [[Kovrov]],\n* [[Tver]],\n* [[Tyumen]],\n* [[Kirov, Kirov Oblast|Kirov]],\n* [[Essentuki]]; \n\n<br />'''[[Belarus]]'''\n\n* [[Brest, Belarus|Brest]]\n* [[Vitebsk]],\n* [[Minsk]]\n\n<br />'''[[Ukraine]]'''\n* [[Khmelnitsky]],\n* [[Vinnitsa]],\n* [[Kharkiv]],\n* [[Kherson]],\n* [[Irpin]],\n* [[Bila Tserkva]],\n* [[Chernivtsi]] \n\n<br />'''[[Armenia]]'''\n\n* [[Yerevan]],\n* [[Yerevan]],\n* [[Gyumri]],\n* [[Sevan, Armenia|Sevan]] \n\n<br />'''Other places'''\n\n* [[B\u0103l\u021bi]] ([[Moldova]]),\n* [[Rybnitsa ]] ([[Transnistria]]),\n* [[Alma-Ata]] ([[Kazakhstan]]),\n* [[Batumi]] ([[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]),\n* [[Tbilisi]] ([[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]),\n* [[Ashgabat]] ([[Turkmenistan]]). \n}}\n\n===Theaters===\n\n* Smolensk Drama Theater. A.S. Griboyedov<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dram-teatrsm.ru/|title=Smolensk State Drama Theater. A.S. Griboyedov|publisher=dram-teatrsm.ru|accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>.\n* Tbilisi has a theater named after A.S. Griboyedov, a monument (author - M.K. Merabishvili) <ref>{{cite web|title=Griboyedov Theatre of Tbilisi|url= http://griboedovtheatre.ge/?lang=en|accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>.\n\n===Museum===\n* The State Historical, Cultural and Natural Museum-Reserve of A.S. Griboyedov \u201cKhmelita\u201d in [[Vyazemsky District, Smolensk Oblast]], [[Russia]].\n* In [[Crimea]], in the Red Cave (Kizil-Koba), a gallery is named in honor of A.S. Griboyedov's stay.\n\n===Libraries===\n* Library of National Literature named after A.S. Griboyedov in [[Saint-Peterburg]].\n* The Central Library named after A.S. Griboyedov of the Centralized Library System # 2 of the Central Administrative District of [[Moscow]]. On the 100th anniversary of the founding of the library, a memorial museum was opened in it, giving A.S. Griboyedov award there <ref>{{cite web|title=Griboyedov award|url=http://kornetobolensky.ru/nagradyi/|lang=en|accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>.\n\n===Other===\n* The last years of the life of A. S. Griboyedov, [[Yury Tynyanov]] devoted the novel \"The Death of Wazir-Mukhtar\" (1928).\n* On April 22, 2014, in St. Petersburg, the [[Grand Lodge of Russia]] created the Lodge of A.S. Griboyedov (No. 45 in the register of VLR)<ref>S.P.\u00a0Karpachov \u00abThe Art of Freemasons\u00bb, \u00abIPC Pareto-Print\u00bb, 2015, p. 475. 2000 {{ISBN|978-5-9905493-1-9}}</ref>.\n* Secondary School named after A. S. Griboyedov ([[Stepanakert]]).\n* Secondary school No. 203 named after A. S. Griboyedov in St. Petersburg.\n* Annual the Moscow City Humanitarian Conference called \"Griboyedov readings\" for research and design work of students<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Griboyedov readings\" project|url=https://griboyedov.org/projects/readings.html|lang=ru|accessdate=2020-02-23}}</ref>.\n* Moscow gymnasium No. 1529 named after A. S. Griboyedov.\n* In Moscow there is a higher educational institution - Institute of International Law and Economics named after A.S. Griboyedov.\n* Scholarship named after A. S. Griboyedov, established by the Academic Council of Lomonosov Moscow State University<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.msu.ru/node/22145|title=Nominal and advanced scholarships, awards and grants for students and post-graduate students of the Faculty of Law {{!}} Faculty of Law, Moscow State University|publisher=www.law.msu.ru|lang=ru|accessdate=2020-02-23}}</ref>.\n* The Airbus 330-243 (VQ-BBF) aircraft of [[Aeroflot]] Airlines is named after A.S. Griboyedov.\n[[File:RR5110-0006R 200-\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u043e \u0434\u043d\u044f \u0440\u043e\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0410.\u0421. \u0413\u0440\u0438\u0431\u043e\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430.gif|thumb|right|200px|Commemorative coin of the Bank of Russia dedicated to the 200th anniversary of the birth of A.S. Griboedov. 2 rubles, silver, 1995]]\n* In 1995, the [[Central Bank of Russia]] issued a coin (2 rubles, silver 500) from the series \u201cOutstanding Personalities of Russia\u201d with the image on the reverse of the portrait of A.S. Griboedov - on the occasion of the 200th anniversary of his birth.\n* Medal \"A.S. Griboedov, 1795-1829\" that was established by the Moscow City Organization of the Union of Writers of the Russian Federation and is awarded to writers, prominent philanthropists and famous publishers for their ascetic activities for the benefit of Russian culture and literature<ref>{{cite web|title=Medal \"A. S. Griboedov 1795 - 1829\" Writers' Union of Russia|url=http://www.lavka-shop.ru/index.php?productID=3631|lang=ru|accessdate=2020-02-23}}</ref>.\n* The Soviet Union released two stamps depicting Griboyedov: 125th Death Anniversary of Alexander Griboyedov stamp (issued in 1954<ref>{{cite web|title=Alexander S. Griboyedov (1795-1829), Russian playwright|url=https://colnect.com/en/stamps/stamp/87485-Alexander_S_Griboyedov_1795-1829_Russian_playwright-125th_Death_Anniversary_of_Alexander_Griboyedov-Soviet_Union_USSR|lang=en|publisher=colnect.com|accessdate=2020-02-23}}</ref>) and a stamp from the Russian Writers series (issued in 1959<ref>{{cite web|title=A.S. Griboyedov|url=https://colnect.com/en/stamps/stamp/144230-A_S_Griboyedov-Russian_Writers-Soviet_Union_USSR|lang=en|publisher=colnect.com|accessdate=2020-02-23}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Vatslav Vorovsky]], Soviet envoy at the Conference of Lausanne, assassinated in 1923\n* [[Pyotr Voykov]], Soviet ambassador to Poland, assassinated in 1927\n* [[Andrei Karlov]], Russian ambassador to Turkey, assassinated in 2016\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Brintlinger, Angela. \"The Persian Frontier: Griboyedov as Orientalist and Literary Hero\". ''Canadian Slavonic Papers'' 45, no. 3 (2003): 371\u2013393.\n*{{mirsky}}\n*[[Laurence Kelly|Kelly, Laurence]]. ''Diplomacy and Murder in Tehran''.\n* Pravda, April 17, 1944, page 4\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Yuri Tynyanov]]: \u0421\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0442\u044c \u0412\u0430\u0437\u0438\u0440-\u041c\u0443\u0445\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0430, 1928\n* [http://vagalecs.narod.ru/Woe.htm A. S. Griboyedov: Woe from Wit (A Four-Act Comedy). Translated from the Russian by A. S. Vagapov].\n* ''El mal de la raz\u00f3n'' (\"\u0413\u043e\u0440\u0435 \u043e\u0442 \u0443\u043c\u0430\"), comedia en cuatro actos, traducci\u00f3n en verso y notas de Oleg Shatrov (incluye una biograf\u00eda detallada de A. Griboi\u00e9dov), Madrid, 2010\n* [[Mary Hobson]]; Aleksandr Sergeyevich Griboyedov. ''Aleksandr Griboyedov's Woe from wit: a commentary and translation''. Edwin Mellen Press; 2005. {{ISBN|978-0-7734-6146-8}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Aleksandr Griboyedov}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |search=( (Alexander OR Aleksandr) AND Griboyedov AND (1829 OR Sergeyevich) )}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=3309}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Griboyedov, Aleksandr}}\n[[Category:1795 births]]\n[[Category:1829 deaths]]\n[[Category:Russian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Russian male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian diplomats]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University alumni]]\n[[Category:19th-century Russian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the Russian Empire to Iran]]\n[[Category:People of the Russo-Persian Wars]]\n[[Category:Russian people murdered abroad]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Iran]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Lion and the Sun]]\n[[Category:Burials in Georgia (country)]]\n[[Category:Attacks on diplomatic missions in Iran]]\n[[Category:19th-century Russian male writers]]\n[[Category:Russian male classical composers]]\n[[Category:Assassinated politicians of the Russian Empire]]\n[[Category:Imperial Moscow University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Russian diplomat, playwright, poet, and composer}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| nickname = \n| image = Griboyedov.jpg\n| caption = Portrait by [[Ivan Kramskoi]]\n| ambassador_from = Russian\n| country = Iran\n| monarch1 = [[Nicholas I of Russia]]\n| primeminister1 = \n| term_start1 = 1828<ref>{{cite book|last1=Borrero|first1=Mauricio|title=Russia: A Reference Guide from the Renaissance to the Present|date=2009|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-0816074754|page=169|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dhm0cGdrTOIC&pg=PA169&dq=griboyedov+appointed+ambassador+1828&hl=nl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQz5P_9sHKAhXJwBQKHUJhC2gQ6AEIMzAC#v=onepage&q=griboyedov%20appointed%20ambassador%201828&f=false}}</ref>\n| term_end1 = 1829\n| predecessor1 = \n| successor1 = \n| office2 = \n| primeminister2 = \n| term_start2 = \n| term_end2 = \n| constituency2 = \n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 = \n| office3 = \n| monarch3 = \n| primeminister3 = \n| term_start3 = \n| term_end3 = \n| predecessor3 = \n| successor3 = \n| birth_name = Alexander Sergeyevich Griboyedov\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1795|01|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Moscow]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1829|02|11|1795|01|15|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Tehran]], [[Qajar Iran]]\n| nationality = [[Imperial Russia|Russian]]\n| residence = \n| restingplace = [[Tiflis]], Russian Empire <small>(present-day [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]])\n| alma_mater = [[Imperial Moscow University|Imperial Moscow University (1808)]]\n| party = \n| otherparty = \n| spouse = [[Nino Chavchavadze]]\n| children = \n| occupation = Diplomat, Playwright, Poet, and Composer\n| profession = \n| cabinet = \n| religion = \n| signature = Griboyedov_Signature.jpg\n| awards = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| blank1 = \n| data1 = \n}}\n'''Alexander Sergeyevich Griboyedov''' ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0413\u0440\u0438\u0431\u043e\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432}}, ''Aleksandr Sergeevich Griboedov'' or ''Sergeevich Griboyedov''; 15 January 1795{{snd}}11 February 1829), formerly [[romanization of Russian|romanized]] as '''Alexander Sergueevich Griboyedoff''',<ref>\"Griboyedoff, Alexander Sergueevich\" in the ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]'', {{nowrap|9th ed.}}, {{nowrap|Vol. XI}} 1880.</ref> was a Russian [[diplomat]], [[playwright]], [[poet]], and [[composer]]. He is recognized as ''[[homo unius libri]]'', a writer of one book, whose fame rests on the verse comedy ''[[Woe from Wit]]'' or ''The Woes of Wit''. He was Russia's ambassador to [[Qajar dynasty|Qajar Persia]], where he and all the embassy staff were massacred by an [[angry mob]] as a result of the rampant anti-Russian sentiment that existed through Russia's imposing of the [[Treaty of Gulistan]] (1813) and [[Treaty of Turkmenchay]] (1828), which had forcefully ratified for Persia's ceding of its northern territories comprising [[Transcaucasia]] and parts of the [[North Caucasus]]. Griboyedov had played a pivotal role in the ratification of the latter treaty.\n\n==Early life==\nGriboyedov was born in [[Moscow]], the exact year unknown, with biographers debating whether it was in 1790 or 1795. Griboyedov received a Masters in [[philology]] from [[Moscow State University|Moscow University]], and subsequently enrolled in the doctorate program. In 1812, he quit the program and enrolled in the military.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Woe from Wit|last=Griboyedov|first=Alexander|publisher=Russian Life Books|year=2017|isbn=978-1-880100-52-3|location=Montpelier, VT|pages=6\u20137}}</ref> He obtained a commission in a [[hussar]] [[regiment]], which he resigned in 1816. The next year, he entered the [[civil service]]. In 1818 he was appointed secretary of the Russian [[legation]] in [[Persia]], and transferred to [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{EB1911|inline=y|wstitle=Griboyedov, Alexander Sergueevich|volume=12|page=593}}</ref>\n\nHis [[Poetry|verse]] comedy ''The Young Spouses'' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u0443\u043f\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0438}}, ''Molodye Suprugi''), which he staged in [[St. Petersburg]] in 1816, was followed by other similar works. Neither these nor his [[essay]]s and poetry would have been long remembered but for the success of his verse comedy ''[[Woe from Wit]]'' ({{lang-ru|\u0413\u043e\u0440\u0435 \u043e\u0442 \u0443\u043c\u0430}}, ''Gore ot Uma''), a [[satire]] on Russian [[aristocracy (class)|aristocratic]] society.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/>\n\nAs a high official in the play puts it, this work is \"a [[pasquinade]] on Moscow\". The play depicts certain social and official stereotypes in the characters of Famusov, who hates reform; his secretary, Molchalin, who fawns over officials; and the aristocratic young liberal and [[Anglomania]]c, Repetilov. By contrast the hero of the piece, Chatsky, an ironic satirist just returned from western Europe, exposes and ridicules the weaknesses of the rest. His words echo the outcry of the young generation in the lead-up to the [[Decembrist|armed insurrection of 1825]].<ref name=\"EB1911\"/>\n\nIn [[Russia]] for the summer of 1823, Griboyedov completed the play and took it to St. Petersburg. It was rejected by the [[censorship|censors]]. Many copies were made and privately circulated, but Griboyedov never saw it published.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/> After his death the manuscript was jointly owned by his wife [[Nino Chavchavadze|Nina Alexandrovna Griboyedova]] and his sister [[Maria Sergeyevna Durnovo (Griboyedova)]].<ref>{{cite magazine|script-title=ru:\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u041e\u0431 \u0410. \u0421. \u0413\u0440\u0438\u0431\u043e\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0435 |trans-title=A note about A. S. Griboyedov |edition=reprint |magazine=Russian Messenger |year=1892 |issue=8 |access-date=29 January 2017 |language=ru |pages=335\u2013347|url=http://feb-web.ru/feb/griboed/critics/vos80/vos_comm.htm }}</ref> The first edition was not published until 1833, four years after his death. Only once did he see it on the stage, when it was performed by the officers of the garrison at [[Yerevan]]. Soured by disappointment, he returned to Georgia. During the [[Russo-Persian War, 1826-1828|Russo-Persian War of 1826\u20131828]], he put his [[Linguistics|linguistic]] expertise at the service of general [[Ivan Paskevich]], a relative; after which he was sent to St. Petersburg where he worked on the [[Treaty of Turkmenchay]] negotiations. There, thinking to devote himself to [[literature]], he started work on a romantic drama, ''A Georgian Night'' ({{lang-ru|\u0413\u0440\u0443\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043d\u043e\u0447\u044c}}, ''Gruzinskaya noch''), based on Georgian legends.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Monument of Alexander Griboyedov in Dilijan Armenia.jpg|thumb|left|Monument erected in Soviet times in [[Dilijan]], [[Armenia]] commemorating the location where [[Alexander Pushkin]] (on his way to meet his brother) stopped the carriage with Alexander Griboyedov's body being transported to [[Tiflis]]. An inscription in Russian and Armenian says: \"Here A. S. Pushkin saw the body of A. S. Griboyedov\".]]\n\nSeveral months after his wedding to [[Nino Chavchavadze|Nino]], 16-year-old daughter of his friend [[Alexander Chavchavadze|Prince Chavchavadze]], Griboyedov was suddenly sent to Persia as [[Minister Plenipotentiary]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} In the aftermath of the [[Russo-Persian War (1826-1828)|war]] and the humiliating [[Treaty of Turkmenchay]], there was strong [[anti-Russian sentiment]] in Persia. Soon after Griboyedov's arrival in [[Tehran]], a mob stormed the [[Embassy of Russia in Tehran|Russian embassy]].\n\nThe incident began when an [[Armenians|Armenian]] [[Eunuch (court official)|eunuch]] escaped from the [[harem]] of the Persian [[Fath Ali Shah|shah]], and at the same time two enslaved Armenian women escaped from the harem of the Shah's son-in-law. All three sought refuge at the Russian legation. As agreed in the [[Treaty of Turkmenchay]], Georgians and Armenians living in Persia at that time were permitted to return to Georgia and [[Eastern Armenia]].<ref name=\"Hopkirk p. 122\">[[Peter Hopkirk|Hopkirk, Peter]]. ''[[The Great Game: The Struggle for Empire in Central Asia]]''. New York: Kodansha Globe, 1997 p. 122 {{ISBN|1-56836-022-3}}</ref> However, the Shah demanded that Griboyedov return the three escapees. Griboyedov refused. His decision caused an uproar throughout the city and several thousand Persians encircled the Russian compound demanding their release.\n\nWhen Griboyedov decided to return the escaped eunuch and two Armenian women, it was too late. Soon after, urged on by the mullahs, the mob stormed the building. A high-ranking Muslim scholar with the title of Mojtahed, Mirza Masih Astarabadi known as Mirza Masih Mojtahed, issued a fatwa saying that freeing Muslim women from the claws of unbelievers is allowed.<ref name=Hopkirk>{{cite book |title=The Great Game |last=Hopkirk |first=Peter |year=2006 |publisher=John Murray |location=London |isbn=978-0-7195-6447-5 |page=113}}</ref>\n\nGriboyedov and other members of his mission had prepared for a siege and sealed all the windows and doors. Armed and in full uniform, they were resolved to defend to the last drop of blood. Although small in number, the [[Cossack]] detachment assigned to protect the legation held off the mob for over an hour until finally being driven back to Griboyedov's office. There, Griboyedov and the Cossacks resisted until the mob broke through the roof of the building, and then through the ceiling, to slaughter them. The escaped eunuch and Griboyedov, who fought with his sword, were among the first to be shot to death; the fate of the two Armenian women remains unknown.<ref name=\"Hopkirk p. 122\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Baron K. K. Bode|title=Griboyedov's Death|url= http://feb-web.ru/feb/griboed/critics/vos29/bode_29.htm|website=www.feb-web.ru}}</ref> Second secretary of the mission Karl Adelung and, in particular, a young doctor whose name is not known, fought hard, but soon the scene was one of butchered, decapitated corpses.\n\nGriboyedov's body, thrown from a window, was decapitated by a kebab vendor who displayed the head on his stall.<ref name=Hopkirk/> The mob dragged the uniformed corpse through the city's streets and bazaars, to cries of celebration. It was eventually abandoned on a garbage heap after three days of ill-treatment by the mob, such that in the end it could be identified only by a duelling injury to a finger. The following June, Griboyedov's friend [[Alexander Pushkin]], travelling through the southern Caucasus, encountered some men from Tehran leading an oxcart. The men told Pushkin they were conveying the ambassador's remains to Tiflis (now [[Tbilisi]]).\nGriboyedov was buried there, in the monastery of St. David ([[Mtatsminda Pantheon]]).<ref name=Hopkirk/>\n\nWhen Nino, Griboyedov's widow, received news of his death she gave premature birth to a child who died a few hours later. Nino lived another thirty years, rejecting all suitors and winning universal admiration for her fidelity to her husband's memory.\n\nIn a move to compensate Russia for the attack and the death of its ambassador, the Shah sent his grandson [[Khosrow Mirza]] to St. Petersburg to avoid another war with [[Tsar Nicholas I]].<ref name=Hopkirk/><ref>George Bournoutian (2014) ''From Tabriz to St. Petersburg: Iran's Mission of Apology to Russia in 1829''</ref> and also gifted to him the [[Shah Diamond]].<ref name=\"Tharoor\">{{Cite news|first=Ishaan |last=Tharoor |title=A Russian ambassador was murdered: The apology came in the shape of a huge diamond |date=22 December 2016 |newspaper=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/12/22/a-russian-ambassador-was-murdered-the-apology-came-in-the-shape-of-a-huge-diamond/ |access-date=29 January 2017 }}</ref>\n\nRussian sources claim that<ref name=\"BournoutianIRA\" /> British agents, who feared Russian influence in Tehran, and Persian reactionaries, who were not satisfied with the Turkmenchay treaty, were responsible for inciting the mob.<ref name=\"BournoutianIRA\" /> The death of Griboyedov, who was a liberal and who advocated regional autonomy for the Christians in Transcaucasia, was probably not a great loss for Tsar Nicholas or General Paskevich, both of whom wished to Russianize the minorities in the Caucasus.{{fact|date=January 2020}} The [[Russo-Turkish War (1828\u201329)]] might have been another reason for the Russian inaction.<ref name=BournoutianIRA>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Bournoutian |first=George| title=Griboyedov, Alexander Sergeevich | encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica | accessdate=2016-02-02|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/griboedov-alexander-sergeevich}}</ref> His wife had written on his tombstone in Tiflis:  \u201cYour mind and works are immortal in Russian memory, but why has my love outlived you?\u201d.<ref name=\"Tharoor\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Moscow Aleksander Griboyedov monument.JPG|thumb|Monument in Moscow]]\n[[File:Griboyedov monument 9122262 22.JPG|thumb|Griboyedov's statue in [[Yerevan]], Armenia]]\nAuthor Angela Brintlinger has said that \"not only did Griboyedov's contemporaries conceive of his life as the life of a literary hero\u2014ultimately writing a number of narratives featuring him as an essential character\u2014but indeed Griboyedov saw himself as a hero and his life as a narrative. Although there is not a literary artifact to prove this, by examining Griboyedov's letters and dispatches, one is able to build a historical narrative that fits the literary and behavioural paradigms of his time and that reads like a real adventure novel set in the wild, wild East.\"\n\nOne of the main settings for [[Mikhail Bulgakov]]'s satirical novel ''[[The Master and Margarita]]'' is named after Griboyedov, as is the [[Griboedov Canal|Griboyedov Canal]] in [[Central Saint Petersburg]]. One of the central streets of [[Tbilisi]], the capital of [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], is named after Griboyedov. This street is crossed by Alexander Chavchavadze street, named after Griboyedov's father-in-law, famous Georgian poet, [[Alexander Chavchavadze]].\n\nOn 17 April 1944 Pravda ran a lengthy feature on the commemoration of Griboyedov's 150th birthday when high-ranking officials, military leaders, diplomats, writers, and artists had attended a celebration in the [[Bolshoi Theatre]]. Novelist and Stalin deputy [[Leonid Leonov]] eulogized Griboyedov, mentioning especially his love of his fatherland.\n\nThe reception to the Shah's grandson Khosrow Mirza in the [[Winter Palace]], and Tsar Nicholas receiving from him the Shah Diamond, are featured in the 2002 Russian film ''[[Russian Ark]]''.\n\n==Commemoration==\n\n===Monuments===\n* In [[Saint Petersburg]], the monument of A.S. Griboyedov (sculptor V.V. Lishev, 1959) is located on Zagorodny Prospekt on Pionerskaya Square (in front of the [[Bryantsev Youth Theatre]])\n* In the center of [[Yerevan]] there is a monument of A.S. Griboyedov (author - Hovhannes Bejanyan, 1974).\n* In [[Alushta]], a monument of A.S. Griboyedov was erected in 2002, on the 100th anniversary of the city.\n* In [[Moscow]], the monument of A.S. Griboyedov is located on Chistoprudny Boulevard.\n* In [[Veliky Novgorod]], A.S. Griboyedov was immortalized in the monument \u201c[[Millennium of Russia]]\u201d, in the group of sculptures \u201cWriters and Artists\u201d.\n* In [[Volgograd]], at the expense of the Armenian community of the city, a bust of A.S. Griboyedov was installed on Sovetskaya Street, in front of Polyclinic \u21163.\n* In [[Tbilisi]], a monument of A.S. Griboyedov is located on the Kura embankment (sculptor M. Merabishvili, architect G. Melkadze, 1961).\n* In [[Tehran]], the Russian [[embassy]] has a monument of A.S. Griboyedov (sculptor V. A. Beklemishev, 1912).\n* A bust of A. S. Griboyedov is installed on the facade of the [[Odessa Opera and Ballet Theater]].\n\n=== Streets ===\nThere are streets n.a. Griboyedov in many cities of Russia and neighboring countries.\n\n{{Hidden\n|List of places\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n| content = '''[[Russia]]'''\n\n* [[Almetyevsk]],\n* [[Petrozavodsk]],\n* [[Perm]],\n* [[Chelyabinsk]],\n* [[Krasnoyarsk]],\n* [[Kaliningrad]],\n* [[Surgut]],\n* [[Simferopol]],\n* [[Sevastopol]],\n* [[Bryansk]],\n* [[Ekaterinburg]],\n* [[Novokuznetsk]],\n* [[Novorossiysk]],\n* [[Novosibirsk]],\n* [[Ryazan]],\n* [[Dzerzhinsk, Russia|Dzerzhinsk]] (Nizhny Novgorod Oblast),\n* [[Irkutsk]],\n* [[Makhachkala]],\n* [[Gelendzhik]],\n* [[Kovrov]],\n* [[Tver]],\n* [[Tyumen]],\n* [[Kirov, Kirov Oblast|Kirov]],\n* [[Essentuki]]; \n\n<br />'''[[Belarus]]'''\n\n* [[Brest, Belarus|Brest]]\n* [[Vitebsk]],\n* [[Minsk]]\n\n<br />'''[[Ukraine]]'''\n* [[Khmelnitsky]],\n* [[Vinnitsa]],\n* [[Kharkiv]],\n* [[Kherson]],\n* [[Irpin]],\n* [[Bila Tserkva]],\n* [[Chernivtsi]] \n\n<br />'''[[Armenia]]'''\n\n* [[Yerevan]],\n* [[Yerevan]],\n* [[Gyumri]],\n* [[Sevan, Armenia|Sevan]] \n\n<br />'''Other places'''\n\n* [[B\u0103l\u021bi]] ([[Moldova]]),\n* [[Rybnitsa ]] ([[Transnistria]]),\n* [[Alma-Ata]] ([[Kazakhstan]]),\n* [[Batumi]] ([[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]),\n* [[Tbilisi]] ([[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]),\n* [[Ashgabat]] ([[Turkmenistan]]). \n}}\n\n===Theaters===\n\n* Smolensk Drama Theater. A.S. Griboyedov<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dram-teatrsm.ru/|title=Smolensk State Drama Theater. A.S. Griboyedov|publisher=dram-teatrsm.ru|accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>.\n* Tbilisi has a theater named after A.S. Griboyedov, a monument (author - M.K. Merabishvili) <ref>{{cite web|title=Griboyedov Theatre of Tbilisi|url= http://griboedovtheatre.ge/?lang=en|accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>.\n\n===Museum===\n* The State Historical, Cultural and Natural Museum-Reserve of A.S. Griboyedov \u201cKhmelita\u201d in [[Vyazemsky District, Smolensk Oblast]], [[Russia]].\n* In [[Crimea]], in the Red Cave (Kizil-Koba), a gallery is named in honor of A.S. Griboyedov's stay.\n\n===Libraries===\n* Library of National Literature named after A.S. Griboyedov in [[Saint-Peterburg]].\n* The Central Library named after A.S. Griboyedov of the Centralized Library System # 2 of the Central Administrative District of [[Moscow]]. On the 100th anniversary of the founding of the library, a memorial museum was opened in it, giving A.S. Griboyedov award there <ref>{{cite web|title=Griboyedov award|url=http://kornetobolensky.ru/nagradyi/|lang=en|accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>.\n\n===Other===\n* The last years of the life of A. S. Griboyedov, [[Yury Tynyanov]] devoted the novel \"The Death of Wazir-Mukhtar\" (1928).\n* On April 22, 2014, in St. Petersburg, the [[Grand Lodge of Russia]] created the Lodge of A.S. Griboyedov (No. 45 in the register of VLR)<ref>S.P.\u00a0Karpachov \u00abThe Art of Freemasons\u00bb, \u00abIPC Pareto-Print\u00bb, 2015, p. 475. 2000 {{ISBN|978-5-9905493-1-9}}</ref>.\n* Secondary School named after A. S. Griboyedov ([[Stepanakert]]).\n* Secondary school No. 203 named after A. S. Griboyedov in St. Petersburg.\n* Annual the Moscow City Humanitarian Conference called \"Griboyedov readings\" for research and design work of students<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Griboyedov readings\" project|url=https://griboyedov.org/projects/readings.html|lang=ru|accessdate=2020-02-23}}</ref>.\n* Moscow gymnasium No. 1529 named after A. S. Griboyedov.\n* In Moscow there is a higher educational institution - Institute of International Law and Economics named after A.S. Griboyedov.\n* Scholarship named after A. S. Griboyedov, established by the Academic Council of Lomonosov Moscow State University<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.msu.ru/node/22145|title=Nominal and advanced scholarships, awards and grants for students and post-graduate students of the Faculty of Law {{!}} Faculty of Law, Moscow State University|publisher=www.law.msu.ru|lang=ru|accessdate=2020-02-23}}</ref>.\n* The Airbus 330-243 (VQ-BBF) aircraft of [[Aeroflot]] Airlines is named after A.S. Griboyedov.\n[[File:RR5110-0006R 200-\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u043e \u0434\u043d\u044f \u0440\u043e\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0410.\u0421. \u0413\u0440\u0438\u0431\u043e\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430.gif|thumb|right|200px|Commemorative coin of the Bank of Russia dedicated to the 200th anniversary of the birth of A.S. Griboedov. 2 rubles, silver, 1995]]\n* In 1995, the [[Central Bank of Russia]] issued a coin (2 rubles, silver 500) from the series \u201cOutstanding Personalities of Russia\u201d with the image on the reverse of the portrait of A.S. Griboedov - on the occasion of the 200th anniversary of his birth.\n* Medal \"A.S. Griboedov, 1795-1829\" that was established by the Moscow City Organization of the Union of Writers of the Russian Federation and is awarded to writers, prominent philanthropists and famous publishers for their ascetic activities for the benefit of Russian culture and literature<ref>{{cite web|title=Medal \"A. S. Griboedov 1795 - 1829\" Writers' Union of Russia|url=http://www.lavka-shop.ru/index.php?productID=3631|lang=ru|accessdate=2020-02-23}}</ref>.\n* The Soviet Union released two stamps depicting Griboyedov: 125th Death Anniversary of Alexander Griboyedov stamp (issued in 1954<ref>{{cite web|title=Alexander S. Griboyedov (1795-1829), Russian playwright|url=https://colnect.com/en/stamps/stamp/87485-Alexander_S_Griboyedov_1795-1829_Russian_playwright-125th_Death_Anniversary_of_Alexander_Griboyedov-Soviet_Union_USSR|lang=en|publisher=colnect.com|accessdate=2020-02-23}}</ref>) and a stamp from the Russian Writers series (issued in 1959<ref>{{cite web|title=A.S. Griboyedov|url=https://colnect.com/en/stamps/stamp/144230-A_S_Griboyedov-Russian_Writers-Soviet_Union_USSR|lang=en|publisher=colnect.com|accessdate=2020-02-23}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Vatslav Vorovsky]], Soviet envoy at the Conference of Lausanne, assassinated in 1923\n* [[Pyotr Voykov]], Soviet ambassador to Poland, assassinated in 1927\n* [[Andrei Karlov]], Russian ambassador to Turkey, assassinated in 2016\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Brintlinger, Angela. \"The Persian Frontier: Griboyedov as Orientalist and Literary Hero\". ''Canadian Slavonic Papers'' 45, no. 3 (2003): 371\u2013393.\n*{{mirsky}}\n*[[Laurence Kelly|Kelly, Laurence]]. ''Diplomacy and Murder in Tehran''.\n* Pravda, April 17, 1944, page 4\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Yuri Tynyanov]]: \u0421\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0442\u044c \u0412\u0430\u0437\u0438\u0440-\u041c\u0443\u0445\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0430, 1928\n* [http://vagalecs.narod.ru/Woe.htm A. S. Griboyedov: Woe from Wit (A Four-Act Comedy). Translated from the Russian by A. S. Vagapov].\n* ''El mal de la raz\u00f3n'' (\"\u0413\u043e\u0440\u0435 \u043e\u0442 \u0443\u043c\u0430\"), comedia en cuatro actos, traducci\u00f3n en verso y notas de Oleg Shatrov (incluye una biograf\u00eda detallada de A. Griboi\u00e9dov), Madrid, 2010\n* [[Mary Hobson]]; Aleksandr Sergeyevich Griboyedov. ''Aleksandr Griboyedov's Woe from wit: a commentary and translation''. Edwin Mellen Press; 2005. {{ISBN|978-0-7734-6146-8}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Aleksandr Griboyedov}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |search=( (Alexander OR Aleksandr) AND Griboyedov AND (1829 OR Sergeyevich) )}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=3309}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Griboyedov, Aleksandr}}\n[[Category:1795 births]]\n[[Category:1829 